# Backend Rules

## API Design

- Follow ASP.NET Core Web API conventions and RESTful API design.
- Use meaningful C# names for classes, methods, and properties.
- Return suitable HTTP status codes (`200`, `201`, `204`, `400`, `404`, `409`, `500`).

## Layering

- Keep controllers thin — route requests, validate input, call services, return responses.
- Put business logic in services, not controllers.
- Use DTOs for request and response payloads.
- Do not expose Entity Framework models directly to the frontend.

## Data Access

- Use `async`/`await` for all database operations.

## Validation & Errors

- Validate all request data (data annotations, FluentValidation, or model binding).
- Handle exceptions properly; map domain errors to appropriate HTTP responses.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD — EF entity returned, sync DB call, logic in controller
[HttpGet("{id}")]
public Product Get(int id) => _context.Products.Find(id);

// ✅ GOOD — DTO response, async service, thin controller
[HttpGet("{id}")]
public async Task<ActionResult<ProductDto>> GetProduct(int id, CancellationToken ct)
{
    var product = await _productService.GetByIdAsync(id, ct);
    return product is null ? NotFound() : Ok(product);
}
```
